    cat: 'selling', slug: 'pre-listing-inspection', title: 'Pre-listing inspections: buying the upper hand',
    short: 'Pre-listing inspection', tease: 'Discover your own surprises first, and negotiation becomes a very different game.',
    metaDesc: 'The case for pre-listing inspections on rural property: controlled repairs, confident pricing, and negotiation advantage.',
    answer: 'A pre-listing inspection lets you discover your property’s issues before buyers do — converting mid-transaction crises into planned line items, pricing confidence, and negotiation advantage. On rural property, extending it to well and septic buys the most leverage of all: those are the surprises that break deals.',
    sections: [
      { h: 'The strategic math', body: [
        'Issues found during a buyer’s contingency carry crisis pricing — repairs negotiated under deadline against exit threats. The same issues found pre-listing carry contractor pricing on your schedule, or become disclosed, priced-in facts that no longer ambush anything.',
        'The confidence dividend compounds: pricing set with full knowledge, marketing claims that inspection later verifies, and buyers reading a documented property as a maintained one — because it demonstrably is.' ] },
      { h: 'Scope for the valley', body: [
        'Out here the meaningful scope includes the rural systems: septic pumped and evaluated, well tested and serviced, wood heat inspected. General home inspection adds the broad sweep. Selective repairs follow the same return logic as all preparation — fix what frightens buyers cheaply, price what does not.',
        'Disclosure interacts simply: known findings join your disclosure obligations, which is a feature — transparent files are what confidence is made of. See the disclosure guide.' ] },
    ],
    rule: 'Pay contractor prices on your calendar, not crisis prices on a buyer’s deadline.',
    faqs: [
      { q: 'Must I fix everything found?', a: 'No — the strategy fork is repair versus disclose-and-price, decided item by item on returns. Control of that choice is precisely what pre-inspection purchases.' },
      { q: 'Do findings have to be disclosed?', a: 'Known material conditions belong in disclosure regardless of how learned — and honest files serve sellers strategically anyway. Surprise, not knowledge, is the enemy.' },
      { q: 'Is this standard practice?', a: 'Among sophisticated rural sellers, increasingly — the leverage is too obvious. I recommend scope case by case; systems first, always.' },
    ],
